  "text": "An investigation of the effects of 9 -THC on human glioblastoma-T98G xenografts demonstrated concentrationdependent effects with low 9 -THC concentrations causing a modest increase in tumor growth and high 9 -THC concentrations promoting tumor cell death [CITATION_1] . Experiments in cultured T98G cells suggested that this effect was mediated by the formation of a functional dimeric complex between GPR55 and CB2 receptors such that low concentrations of 9 -THC activated the CB2 receptor and Erk expression thereby promoting tumor cell growth. However, in the presence of high 9 -THC concentrations, 9 -THC inhibited GPR55 which blocked the CB2 receptor and Erk activation thereby inhibiting tumor cell growth. This finding is consistent with reports showing that the putative G-protein-coupled cannabinoid receptor, GPR55, is overexpressed in cancers and promotes carcinogenesis [CITATION_2] .",
